nodes.title: Metabolomics reveals betaine as a biomarker for better boar spermatozoa freezability
nodes.description: Artificial insemination in the pig industry requires frozen semen of better freezability and post-thaw quality. Several recent metabolomics studies were carried out to discover sperm freezability-related biomarkers. However, only were limited number of pig breeds examined and results remain obscure. Here, boar semen samples were collected and quality evaluated for 3 Western breeds (Duroc, Landrace and Yorkshire), originated from a nucleus farm and a boar station. Post-thaw sperm from the nucleus farm exhibited significantly higher motility and vitality rates (P < 0.01), and also better acrosome integrity and plasma membrane integrity (P < 0.05). For the high and low freezability groups (36 samples in total), ultra high-performance liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (UHPLC-MS) on spermatozoa identified significantly differential metabolites (P < 0.05, including betaine), with 258 metabolites in Duroc, 126 in Landrace, and 215 in Yorkshire, which were significantly enriched in 11, 8 and 13 metabolic pathways (KEGG) (P < 0.05), respectively. Besides breed-specific pathways (Duroc: cysteine and methionine metabolism; Landrace: arginine and proline metabolism, tryptophan metabolism, lysine degradation, galactose metabolism and pyruvate metabolism; Yorkshire: steroid hormone biosynthesis, riboflavin metabolism and linoleic acid metabolism), two pathways common to 3 breeds (alanine, aspartate and glutamate metabolism, and pentose phosphate pathway) were found. Betaine was confirmed to be at significantly higher level in semen of high freezability for all 3 pig breeds (P < 0.05). Taken together, metabolites and metabolic pathways common and specific to commercial Western breeds were identified. Betaine was related to better spermatozoa freezability. Our findings provide the basis and insights into better understanding the role of metabolic molecules and pathways important to boar spermatozoa freezability.

nodes.name: Chromatography
nodes.description: The samples were separated using an ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC) system (Agilent 1290 Infinity LC, Hangzhou, China) with a HILIC column. The column temperature was maintained at 25C, with a flow rate of 0.3 mL/min and an injection volume of 2 L. The mobile phase consisted of: (A) water + 25 mM ammonium acetate + 25 mM ammonia, and (B) acetonitrile. The gradient elution program was as follows: 01.5 min, 98% B; 1.512 min, B linearly decreased from 98% to 2%; 1214 min, B maintained at 2%; 1414.1 min, B linearly increased from 2% to 98%; 14.117 min, B maintained at 98%. Throughout the analysis, samples were kept in a 4C autosampler. To avoid the impact of instrument signal fluctuations, samples were analyzed in a randomized order. Quality control (QC) samples were inserted into the sample queue to monitor and evaluate the stability of the system, and the reliability of the experimental data.

nodes.name: Data transformation
nodes.description: The raw LCMS data were first converted to .mzXML format using ProteoWizard software . The converted data were imported into XCMS for peak detection, retention time correction, peak alignment, and peak area extraction. The resulting feature matrix was further processed for data normalization, batch correction, and quality assessment prior to downstream statistical analysis.

nodes.name: Extraction
nodes.description: After the frozen sperm were slowly thawed at 4C, a pre-cooled methanol/acetonitrile/water solution (2:2:1, v/v) was added. The mixture was vortexed thoroughly, followed by low-temperature ultrasonication for 30 minutes. It was then allowed to stand at -20C for 10 minutes, and centrifuged at 14,000 g at 4C for 20 minutes. The supernatant was collected and vacuum-dried. The dried residue was reconstituted in 100 L of an acetonitrile/water solution (acetonitrile:water = 1:1, v/v), vortexed again, and centrifuged at 14,000 g at 4C for 15 minutes. The resulting supernatant was collected for  LC-MS detection.

nodes.name: Mass spectrometry
nodes.description: After separation by the UHPLC system, samples were analyzed using the AB Triple TOF 6600 mass spectrometer (SCIEX, Shanghai, China), to acquire both primary and secondary spectra of the samples. Detection was performed in both positive and negative ion modes using electrospray ionization (ESI). The ESI source and mass spectrometry parameters were set as follows: sheath gas (Gas1): 60, auxiliary gas (Gas2): 60, curtain gas (CUR): 30 psi, ion source temperature: 600C, spray voltage (ISVF): 5500 V (for both positive and negative modes). The primary mass-to-charge ratio (m/z) detection range was 801200 Da, with a resolution of 60,000 and a scan accumulation time of 100 ms. For secondary spectra, a segmented acquisition method was used, with a scan range of 701200 Da, a resolution of 30,000, a scan accumulation time of 50 ms, and a dynamic exclusion time of 4 s.

nodes.name: Metabolite identification
nodes.description: Metabolite identification was performed using a locally established in-house standard library provided by Shanghai Applied Protein Technology Co., Ltd. (Luo et al., 2017; Zhao et al., 2018). Annotation was conducted by matching experimental data to reference standards based on multiple orthogonal parameters, including retention time, accurate mass tolerance (25 ppm), MS/MS fragmentation spectral similarity, and collision energy patterns. All automatically annotated metabolites were further subjected to manual verification to confirm annotation accuracy. The confidence level of metabolite identification followed the criteria of the Metabolomics Standards Initiative (MSI) and was assigned as Level 2.

nodes.name: Sample collection
nodes.description:
Healthy and fertile boars from 3 breeds (20-month-old Large White, Landrace and Duroc) originated from one nucleus farm and one boar station were selected. Semen was collected using the gloved hand method, removing the gel in the semen by gauze.

The collected semen was immediately placed in a 37C incubator for 10 minutes. Then, 10 L of the sample was dropped onto a pre-warmed sperm counting chamber, and sperm quality (concentration, morphology, motility, rate of normal sperms, etc.) was evaluated using the AccuCell Photometer (IMV technologies, France) and Computer-Assisted Sperm Analysis (CASA) system (Line-HY, Chongqing, China). For each sample, four non-consecutive fields of view were selected, with each field containing over 1000 sperm. Semen samples with sperm motility above 75% were considered qualified and used for subsequent procedures.
